<AbstractNarration>AST-0504947&lt;br/&gt;Burrows, Adam&lt;br/&gt;University of Arizona&lt;br/&gt;Multi-Dimensional Simulations of Core-Collapse Supernovae&lt;br/&gt;ABSTRACT&lt;br/&gt;Recently developed fully 2D multi-group, multi-angle radiation/hydrodynamics codes&lt;br/&gt;will be used to investigate the roles of progenitor rotation, aspherical neutrino emissions,&lt;br/&gt;hydrodynamic instabilities, and initial mass on neutrino driven mechanisms of core&lt;br/&gt;collapse supernovae. The need for this work is motivated by the significant uncertainties&lt;br/&gt;in the process by which such supernovae explode (e.g., how is the stalled shock&lt;br/&gt;revived?). Special attention will be paid to the role of rotation and anisotropic neutrino&lt;br/&gt;heating on the viability of the supernova explosion. Beyond this, several other aspects&lt;br/&gt;will also be explored including: resulting iron distributions, the degree of top-bottom&lt;br/&gt;asymmetry, different treatments/coding of the underlying physics, neutrino and&lt;br/&gt;gravitational wave signatures, and pulsar kick mechanisms. The work here will directly&lt;br/&gt;contribute to the training of two graduate students, as well as improve our understanding&lt;br/&gt;of these important and complex events.</AbstractNarration>
